one species focus, like guppies / bettas / livebearers / easy community fish

That fits the description already visible on the channel.

2. Make titles less “what happened” and more “why should I click”
In aquarium YouTube, views usually come from:

a problem: “Why my guppies keep dying”
a comparison: “Best beginner fish: guppy vs betta”
a result: “How I cleared green water in 3 days”
a transformation: “Before and after my 10 gallon tank”

Good small-channel examples:

“5 Beginner Fish That Are Actually Easy”
“3 Reasons Your Guppies Keep Dying”
“My Betta Tank Upgrade on a Budget”
“Top 5 Mistakes New Fish Keepers Make”
“Why This Sponge Filter Is Better Than You Think”

3. Use Shorts to feed long videos
With only a small subscriber base, Shorts are a good discovery tool. The channel search result also points to a Shorts tab.
Use Shorts for:

feeding clips
fish close-ups
tank glow-ups
15-second beginner tips
“one mistake, one fix” clips

Then pin a comment like:
“Full video on setting up this tank on my channel.”

4. Thumbnail rule: one fish, one idea
Do not make thumbnails busy. For fish content, small channels do best when the thumbnail shows:

one clear fish or one tank shot
2–4 words max
strong contrast
no tiny text

Examples:

“Beginner Fish”
“Tank Mistakes”
“Guppy Tips”
“Cloudy Water?”

5. Open the video faster
For small channels, the first 10 seconds matter a lot. Skip long intros. Start with:

the fish
the problem
the result
the question

Example:
“Today I’m showing 3 mistakes that kill beginner guppies, and one of them is super common.”

6. Post in series
Instead of random uploads, make mini-series:

“Beginner Fish School” episode 1, 2, 3
“My Guppy Tank Journey” episode 1, 2, 3
“Cheap Aquarium Upgrades” episode 1, 2, 3

That helps people watch more than one video, which matters more than one-off views.

7. Aim at searchable beginner questions
Your description already says beginner advice, which is a good niche.
Make videos answering questions people actually search:

best fish for beginners
guppy care
betta care
cloudy tank water
fish tank cycling
sponge filter setup
how many fish in a tank
beginner aquarium plants

These are more likely to get steady search traffic than pure diary-style uploads.

8. Use comments and community to find topics
Ask simple questions:

“What fish should I cover next?”
“Guppies or bettas?”
“Do you want more beginner tips or tank updates?”

That gives you future topics and helps viewers feel involved.

9. One upload rhythm is enough
For this size channel, a strong rhythm would be:

2 Shorts per week
1 full video per week

That is enough to learn what works without burning out.

